    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Budget Surplus Fever</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Stephen E Haebig letter, commenting on July 9 editorial, questions whether projections of budget surpluses will hold up</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Less Money Than Meets the Eye'' (editorial, July 9), about carving up the projected $4.2 trillion surplus:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Less Money Than Meets the Eye'' (editorial, July 9), about carving up the projected $4.2 trillion surplus:</p>
        <p>I would just like to ask, Will the projections hold up? We don't have the money in hand; we are just told that it will show up. Since forecasting the economy 10 years in advance is usually on the foolhardy side, why are we figuring out how to spend that money? Or is this just writing more checks that we won't be able to cash?  STEPHEN E. HAEBIG  Chapel Hill, N.C., July 9, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
